The Dirac delta distribution, also known as the delta function, is a generalized function that is used to represent a spike or impulse at a specific point in a continuous signal. Mathematically, it is defined as:

δ(t) = { 0 for t ≠ 0,  ∞ for t = 0 }

It has the properties of being normalized (i.e., the total area under the curve of the delta function is equal to 1) and acting as a filter, in the sense that the convolution of a continuous function with the delta function at a specific point yields the value of that function at that point.
